

Atomic Associative Array

Extendible hashing
Directory uses radix sharding by 1024 to minimize handling copy latency on global expansions and increase concurrency. 
Radix shards are SOA structures with routing shards for the hot path and allocation shards for bucket splits or global expansions.
SOA Shard handles are inlined, the shards store handles into mmapped arenas. 
Directory shards handles are stored in one mmap arena split by 1024.. The buckets have a separate larger a mmap arena.
Directory uses atomic EBR pointer to mmap directory u32 handles to avoid dangling pointers on expansion.

Buckets
We use the hash trie of the global len to index into the directory to get the buckets handle. The bucket itself stores 16 key-value pairs.
We SIMD scan over 16 u8 fingerprints set to check for collision. Then before a key comparison which required a mmap pointer hop we compare an inlined u16 second fingerprint.
The bucket uses an atomic u32 to control ref counts and locks for spin locks and atomic operations to avoid mutex locks and deadlocks to allow per shard concurrency.
Writers block readers, readers dont block.





RUSTFLAGS="-C target-cpu=native" cargo test --release -- --nocapture
